<h1>To Richard Washington</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon 27th Septr 1763.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>In July62 I received the Copy of your Letter of the 27th of April preceeding<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0001-ptr">1</a>By Captn Braisse it came, &amp; superscribed with a Box, but no Box appeared, nor did I much wonder at it, it being the Copy of a Letter only, and the Captns disavowing the receipt of any such Packagesome considerable time after this I was favoured with the original Letter, but by what Ship it was brought, I am to this day ignorant, for neither the Ships nor the captains name was mentioned, and alth your Letter began with saying you Inclose the Captns receipt (for the Box) no such receipt was found, nor Invoice or Bill of Costs, nor mention made who this Captn was: finding myself reduced to this dilemma, and left without a footstep of enquiry, I resolved to wait for further explanation; or till I shoud hear of the Box before I gave you the trouble of a Letter, but neither of these happening till Collo. Fairfax presented me with your obliging favour of the 13th of April last, I began to despair of the desired information, however upon receipt of that Letter I immediately dispatched a Servant to Mr Middleton at Annapolis from whose Wife (he not being at home) I got the Inclosed answerwhat it is I have further to expect in this matter you can best resolve.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>In the Event of your ever visiting America, I am in hopes you will not think a little time ill spent in a small Tower to VirginiaWe have few things here striking to European Travellers (except an abundant Woods)but a little varietya welcome reception among a few friendsand the open and prevalent hospitality of the Country in general, might perhaps proove agreable for a while; &amp; I must be permitted to add, that I shall think myself very happy in seeing you at Mt Vernon where you might depend upon finding the most cordial entertainment.</p>
<p>The Indians at a time when we thought ourselves fixed in the utmost tranquility, have, in open violation of the Treaty recommenced Hostilities, and (by a sudden Irruption) thrown the
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-07-02-pb-0258">[258]</span>
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-07-02-pb-0259">[259]</span>

<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-07-02-pb-0260">[260]</span>
Frontiers of almost all the Colonies into terrible consternationThey have lately met with some pretty rugged treatment, and it is hoped they will sue for Terms again in a very little while.</p>
<p>I dined at Belvoir yesterday, and left the Family in perfect healthas also Doctr CockburnesMrs Washington makes a tender of her Compliments and I am Dr Sir Yr Most Obedt Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0154-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 GW wrote at the bottom of this copy of the letter, By the TryalCaptn Wm McGachin.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0073" class="document">Richard Washingtons letter of 27 April 1762</a> has not been found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0154-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0120" class="document">Richard Washingtons letter of 13 April 1763</a> has not been found. The missing Box supposedly contained the clothes GW ordered from Washington, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0050" class="document">20 Oct. 1761</a>. Neither the clothes nor the box was ever received (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0253" class="document">GW to Washington, 20 Sept. 1765,</a> and notes). Samuel Horatio Middleton was a tavern keeper in Annapolis who was involved in trade.</p>

</div>
